Making a Movie Popular

Thousands of movies are released every year, yet not all are welcomed by audiences. Numerous variables may affect the popularity of movies.

In this project, we are going to find out the attributes of making a movie popular, and try to predict a movie using a multiple linear regression model that will be developed later.

Load data

load("/Rachel/Study/Linear Regression and Modeling/Week 4/Movie Data.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The original data were gathered from 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016. 32 different variables were contained in the dataset,including numerical and categorical ones, as well as information from Rotten Tomatoes and IMDB for reference.

The data can be generalized to all US movies because of the randomly selection of the data. And no causality can be inferred.

Not all variables will be used in the project, since some of them are only for informational purposes and do not make any sense to reach a statistical result.

Therefore, we create a new dataset (movies_new) based on the original one, through selecting and combining some variables.

movies_new <- movies[c(1:3,6,18,4,13,16,5,15,17,19:26)]

Part 2: Research question

Now we come to the project purpose to clarify what the research question is. As stated at the beginning, this project wants to explore the attributes making a movie popular with the data in hand. In this sense, the new dataset adjusted the order and number of variables presented in the original one, putting the audience_score in the first column as a response variable while others are regarded as explanatory variables.

Analysing the collected data, it is interesting to see whether imdb_rating and critics_score do affect popularity of a movie, and visualize the relationships with multiple linear regression model between audience_score and imdb-rating & critics_score. We also want to see what other categorical variables may affect the result. We may hopefully use the model to predict the popularity of new movies.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

Since we already had dataset in hand, we will do exploratory data analysis (EDA) in this part.

Firstly, we will see the relationships between audience_score and imdb_rating & critics_score:

ggplot(data = movies_new, aes(x = audience_score, y = imdb_rating)) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

ggplot(data = movies_new, aes(x = audience_score, y = critics_score)) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

It looks like that audience_score has strong relationships with imdb_rating and critics_score.

We will check the reliability of our hypotheses in the next part as well as the relationships between audience_score and categorial variables.

Part 4: Modeling

Compared with the original (movies) and the new (movies_new) dataset we created before, we have excluded some variables such as thtr_rel_month, thtr_rel_day, dvd_rel_month, dvd_rel_day. Actor2, actor3, actor4 and actor5 are also omitted as it is meaningless to have so many levels of actor. Imdb_url and rt_url only provide information for reference, thus, they are also omitted.

Now, let’s start to test hypothese using Backwards Elimination with the adjusted R squared approach.

The reason for choosing backwards elimination with the adjusted R squared approach is that we are still not sure which variables are significant to the result with many variables in hand. We would like to start with a full model and drop one varible at a time to see whether the omitting would make changes of the model. Adjusted R squared approach is better for model selection as we are going to develop a model for prediction, and does not need to apply different models with different significant levels.

movies_full <- lm(audience_score ~ title_type + genre + runtime + imdb_rating + critics_score + mpaa_rating + critics_rating + audience_rating + best_pic_nom + best_pic_win + best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_dir_win + top200_box, data = movies_new)
summary(movies_full)$adj.r.squared
## [1] 0.8846785

Then we may remove one variable for each time and re-caculate the value of adjusted R squared.

We can do some sample caculation here: Firstly, let’s remove title_type from the explanatory variables list, and use command:

movies_full1 <- lm(audience_score ~ genre + runtime + imdb_rating + critics_score + mpaa_rating + critics_rating + audience_rating + best_pic_nom + best_pic_win + best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_dir_win + top200_box, data = movies_new)
summary(movies_full1)$adj.r.squared

Then, we drop the next variable genre.

movies_full2 <- lm(audience_score ~ title_type + runtime + imdb_rating + critics_score + mpaa_rating + critics_rating + audience_rating + best_pic_nom + best_pic_win + best_actor_win + best_actress_win + best_dir_win + top200_box, data = movies_new)
summary(movies_full2)$adj.r.squared

Repeat to develop smaller models, and finally we can reach to the parsimonious model that no increase appeared in adjusted R squared when removing variables following command:

movies_full <- lm(audience_score ~ runtime + imdb_rating + critics_score + genre + audience_rating + best_pic_nom + best_actress_win, data = movies_new)
summary(movies_full)

Looking back to our hypotheses, imdb_rating and critics_score are in the model, thus they are significant to the popularity of a movie and our hypotheses are correct. Besides, variables including genre, audience_rating, best_pic_nom, and best_actress_win are also affect the popularity.

Part 5: Prediction

With the model developed, we would like to predict a movie from 2016 - The Jungle Book. The link from IMDB is: https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3040964/?pf_rd_m=A2FGELUUNOQJNL&pf_rd_p=ea4e08e1-c8a3-47b5-ac3a-75026647c16e&pf_rd_r=3BRSEHW93QCRYVG0MD6C&pf_rd_s=center-1&pf_rd_t=15506&pf_rd_i=moviemeter&ref_=chtmvm_tt_87, and the link of Rotten Tomatoes is: https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_jungle_book_2016.

Firstly, we will create a new data frame for this movie.

newmovie <- data_frame(runtime = 106, genre = "Drama", imdb_rating = 7.4, critics_score = 95, audience_rating = "Upright", best_pic_nom = "no", best_actress_win = "no")
newmovie
## # A tibble: 1 x 7
##   runtime genre imdb_rating critics_score audience_rating best_pic_nom
##     <dbl> <chr>       <dbl>         <dbl> <chr>           <chr>       
## 1     106 Drama         7.4            95 Upright         no          
## # ... with 1 more variable: best_actress_win <chr>

Then, we can do the prediction:

predict(movies_full, newmovie)
##        1 
## 79.97778

We can also construct a prediction interval around this prediction, which will provide a measure of uncertainty around the prediction.

predict(movies_full, newmovie, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
##        fit     lwr      upr
## 1 79.97778 66.5331 93.42246

Hence, we may predict that the movie is expected to have the popularity between 66.53 and 93.42. Let’s look back to the observed value of popularity from IMDB - 87. It is within the prediction interval around 79.97, thus, we may confident present this multiple linear regression model for predicting the popularity of a movie.

Next, let’s do diagnostics for the model.

Nearly Normal Residuals: we are going to use histogram to check.

hist(movies_full$residuals)

Besides, we can also use a normal probability plot of the residuals for checking.

qqnorm(movies_full$residuals)

We saw a nearly normal distribution of residuals centered at 0 here.

Constant Variability of Residuals: We will use residuals plots to check.

plot(movies_full$residuals ~ movies_full$fitted)

Residuals are equally variable for low and high values of the response variables.

Independent Residuals: residuals plots are used to check.

plot(movies_full$residuals)

Now, we can safely present this model as our final model since it passed the diagnostics.

Part 6: Conclusion

To sum up, this multiple linear regression model may be helpful in finding out what attributes make a movie popular and predicting the popularity with a visulized number. That is the imdb_rating and critics_score do have significant linear relationships with audience_score, while the popularity is also effected by genre of a movie, audience’s rating, whether it is nominated as the best picture of Oscar, etc.

However, this project also has room for improvements since the caculations in building the model took a long time to repeat as we drop one variable each time for seeking a best model. We may hope to address this problem in the future study.
